{"title_page": "Animalympics", "text_new": "{{short description|1980 animated film by Steven Lisberger}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Animalympics\n| image                    = Animalympics.jpg\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = Promotional release poster\n| genre                    = \n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = \n| writer                   = [[Steven Lisberger]]<br>Michael Fremer\n| screenplay               = \n| story                    = Steven Lisberger<br>[[Roger Allers]]<br>John Norton\n| director                 = Steven Lisberger\n| starring                 = [[Billy Crystal]]<br>Michael Fremer<br>[[Gilda Radner]]<br>[[Harry Shearer]]\n| music                    = [[Graham Gouldman]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| producer                 = [[Donald Kushner]]<br>Steven Lisberger<br>Peggy Flook Lisberger (associate producer)\n| editor                   = Matt Cope\n| cinematography           = Ted Bemiller<br>Paul Nevitt<br>(animation camera)\n| runtime                  = 75 minutes\n| company                  = [[Lisberger Studios]]\n| distributor              = [[Warner Bros.]] (U.S. video and TV rights)\n| network                  = [[NBC]]\n| released                 = {{start date|1980|2|1}}\n| website                  = \n}}\n'''''Animalympics''''' is a 1980 [[Animated film|animated]] [[television film]] directed by [[Steven Lisberger]]<ref>[https://filmschoolrejects.com/27-things-we-learned-from-the-tron-commentary-89ed3c066303/ 27 Things We Learned from the 'Tron' Commentary - Film School Rejects]</ref> and produced by [[Lisberger Studios]] for the [[NBC]] network.<ref>[https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/how-furries-became-a-fandom How Furries Became a Fandom|SYFY]</ref> Originally commissioned as two separate specials, it spoofs the [[Summer Olympic Games|Summer]] and [[Winter Olympic Games]] and features the voices of [[Billy Crystal]], [[Gilda Radner]], [[Harry Shearer]] and Michael Fremer.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Animated TV Specials: The Complete Directory to the First Twenty-Five Years, 1962-1987 |date=1989 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-2198-2 |accessdate=27 March 2020 |url=https://archive.org/details/animatedtvspecia0000wool/page/14/mode/2up |page=14}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film is a series of vignettes presented as the broadcast of the first animal Olympic Games through the fictional ZOO television network. The Games combine summer and winter Olympic events.\n\nThe event is covered mostly by Barbara Warblers, a stork, and \"anchorturtle\" Henry Hummel. The [[100-meter dash]] is covered in the style of a [[drag racing|drag race]] by Jackie Fuelit.\n\nUnlike the real Olympics, continents are represented rather than countries. The continents featured are North America, South America, [[Eurasia]], Europe, Africa, Australia, and Asia. Eurasia represents the [[USSR]], whereas Europe represents Western and Central Europe.\n\nThe only mention of areas other than continents are the New York City Rats soccer team, Dean Wilson being from California, a Central American marathon runner named Pep\u00e9 Repanosa, an [[Acapulco]] cliff diver named \"Primo Cabeza\", marathon runner Terry Hornsby being from [[Boulder, Colorado]], Ren\u00e9 Fromage being from France, and Kurt W\u00fcfner appearing at the [[Alpine skiing|downhill]] event right before a [[Scandinavia]]n is given a gold medal.\n\nAlthough many of the segments stand alone, there are some recurring events and important characters. The largest such story is the coverage of the [[marathon (sport)|marathon]], where competitors Ren\u00e9 Fromage and Kit Mambo are the favorites to win. Both are determined to win \u2013 Fromage having devoted his entire life to the marathon, Mambo determined to make a name for herself \u2013 they find themselves surprised when their minds wander to thoughts of mutual admiration and then to love, culminating in the pair holding hands for the rest of the race and crossing the finish line together.  Another important story is that of Kurt W\u00fcffner, a West German [[dachshund]] [[skiing|skier]], and his disappearance to [[Shangri-la|Dogra-la]] during a mountain climbing expedition shortly after the [[slalom skiing|slalom]] event.\n\nA minor story features an [[American alligator|alligator]] named Bolt Jenkins. He was \"born as a handbag\" and told he would never walk again. A song during his story reveals that he lives in the [[Sanitary sewer|sewers]]. After seeing a frog named Boris Amphibiensky break the world record for the [[high jump]], Jenkins has an epiphany, and becomes determined to break the record. Jenkins goes on to set world records in the high jump, the [[pole vault]], and later the [[100-meter dash]]. Jenkins sacrifices his gold medal in the hundred meter dash to an African competitor and favorite whom Jenkins considers to be his superior.\n\nSome events are only referenced rather than being covered. In the song \"We've Made It to the Top\", various events are shown that are otherwise not covered:\n*[[Hammer Throw]]\n*[[Shot put]]\n*[[Javelin throw|Javelin]]\n*[[Cycling]]\n*[[Relay Racing]]\n*[[Discus]]\n*[[Field hockey]]\n\nAlso referenced but not covered:\n*[[Boxing]]- only a highlight reel is provided after the match, despite being previewed as \"coming up after the basketball game\"\n*[[Speed Skating]]- previewed, but not actually shown\n*[[Water Polo]]- mentioned as happening earlier in the week\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Gilda Radner]] as Barbra Warblers / Brenda Springer / Cora Lee Perrier / Tatyana Tushenko / Dorrie Turnell / The Contessa\n* [[Billy Crystal]] as Rugs Turkell / Joey Gongolong / Art Antica\n* [[Harry Shearer]] as Keen Hacksaw / Mayor of Animalympic Island / Burnt Woody / Mark Spritz\n* Michael Fremer as Henry Hummel / Ren\u00e9 Fromage / Kit Mambo / Bolt Jenkins / Kurt Wuffner / Dean Wilson / Mele / Count Maurice Boar-Deaux / Jackie Fuelit / Bear McLane / Guy Lafluke / Bjorn Freeborg / Mamo Ululu\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/movies/Animalympics/|title=Animalympics|work=Behind the Voice Actors|date=September 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n''Animalympics'' was commissioned by [[NBC]] in 1978, as the network intended [[Lisberger Studios]] to create it as two hour-long specials to be paired alongside coverage of both the [[1980 Winter Olympics]] and the [[1980 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] then held in [[Moscow]]. But after the [[Soviet Union]] had [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War|invaded and gained control of Afghanistan]], then [[United States]] President [[Jimmy Carter]] decided to [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|boycott the Moscow Summer Olympics]]. Because of this, NBC canceled its [[NBC Olympic broadcasts|Olympic coverage]] and the Animalympics Summer special.<ref name=\"Toon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toonopedia.com/animalym.htm|title=ANIMALYMPICS|work=[[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]|last=D. Markstein|first=Donald|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, from its conception, producer [[Donald Kushner]] and director Steven Lisberger intended the project as a feature-length theatrical release recorded and mixed in [[Dolby Stereo|Dolby surround sound]] via magnetically striped 35mm film even though The Winter Olympics special was considered for an [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film]] nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cartoonresearch.com/index.php/cartoons-considered-for-an-academy-award-1979/|title=Cartoons Considered For An Academy Award \u2013 1979 -|website=Cartoonresearch.com|accessdate=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAmong those who worked on ''Animalympics'' were art director/animator [[Roger Allers]], animation director [[Bill Kroyer]], and animator [[Brad Bird]]. Allers, who animated Kit Mambo, the lion star of ''Animalympics,'' went on to direct ''[[The Lion King]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reelzchannel.com/persondetail.aspx?personid=97623|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061030035246/http://www.reelzchannel.com/persondetail.aspx?personid=97623|url-status=dead|title=Roger Allers \u2013 Movies, Movie Clips and Trailers<!-- Bot generated title -->|archivedate=October 30, 2006}}</ref> Kroyer later wrote and directed the Oscar-nominated short ''[[Technological Threat]]'' and the animated feature ''[[FernGully: The Last Rainforest]].'' [[Brad Bird]] went on to work as story editor of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', and later achieved even greater success writing and directing ''[[The Iron Giant]]'', ''[[The Incredibles]]'' and ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]''. Director Lisberger went on to conceive, co-write and direct the science fiction [[cult film|cult]] [[cult following|classic]] ''[[Tron]]'', which some of the ''Animalympics'' crew were involved in. Its soundtrack supervisor was Michael Fremer, who was involved in ''Animalympics'' as a co-writer, voice artist, dialogue/music track editor and sound mix supervisor. Fremer went on to supervise the Academy Award nominated soundtrack to ''[[Tron]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keyframeonline.com/Animation/Animalympics/434/|title=Animalympics|first=Athena|last=Cooper|website=Keyframeonline.com|accessdate=January 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919160109/http://www.keyframeonline.com/Animation/Animalympics/434/|archive-date=September 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Main|Animalympics (soundtrack)}}\n[[A&M Records]] in the US, and [[Mercury Records]] in Europe released an [[Animalympics soundtrack]] album, which has long been out of print. The music on this soundtrack was written and produced by [[Graham Gouldman]], who performed the tracks himself along with other members of [[10cc]] (Gouldman was the bassist for the band at the time).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Graham-Gouldman-Animalympics-Music-From-The-Original-Motion-Picture-Soundtrack/release/1050728 |title=Graham Gouldman \u2013 ''Animalympics \u2013 Music from the Original Motion Picture Soundtrack'' LP|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nPieces of classical music play in the film. \"The Hut on Hen's Legs (Baba Yaga)\" from ''[[Pictures at an Exhibition]]'' by [[Modest Mussorgsky]] plays during Tatyana Tushenko's floor exercises. \"March to the Scaffold\" from ''[[Symphonie fantastique]]'' by [[Hector Berlioz]] plays during the couple's figure skating. The 3rd movement from [[Symphony No. 4 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 4]] by [[Johannes Brahms]] plays during Dorie Turnell's skating performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.org/details/Animalympics_201704|title=Animalympics|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nDespite the 1980 NBC premiere being cancelled midway, [[Lisberger Studios]] prepared a theatrical version for overseas markets by editing together the [[Summer Olympic Games|Summer]] and [[Winter Olympic Games]] sections, alongside other additions and changes to increase it's run-time for theatrical exhibition. Though ''Animalympics'' never found a theatrical distributor in the U.S., [[Warner Bros.]] did acquire US home video and pay-TV distribution rights to it shortly after the NBC cancellation. It eventually got a full US TV premiere on NBC affiliate WPTZ on July 4, 1982. Animalympics also aired in its theatrical form on [[HBO]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasertimepodcast.com/2016/08/15/animalympics-the-forgotten-animated-movie-about-animals-in-the-olympics/|title=Animalympics: The Forgotten Animated Movie About Animals in the Olympics|work=Laser Time Podcast|last=Ant|first=C.|date=August 15, 2016|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forcesofgeek.com/2016/08/run-forever-26-years-of-animalympics.html|title=Run Forever: 26 Years of 'Animalympics'|work=Forces of Geek|last=Maxwell|first=Erin|date=August 5, 2016|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-best-animated-kids-movies-youve-never-seen/|title=The Best Animated Kids Movies You've Probably Never Seen|work=[[/Film]]|last=Hunter|first=Rob|date=June 27, 2017|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> and [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] nationwide in summer 1984,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cartoonresearch.com/index.php/animation-anecdotes-277/|title=Animation Anecdotes #277: The Story of Animalympics.|work=Cartoon Research|date=August 26, 2016|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> as well as intermittently during the early to mid-1990s on [[The Disney Channel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/corbin-times-tribune-feb-07-1998-p-18/|title=Corbin Times Tribune Archives, Feb 7, 1998, p. 18|date=February 7, 1998|website=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n===Availability===\nThe film was released on VHS by Warner Brothers, [[UAV Corporation]] and [[Family Home Entertainment]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Animalympics|date=December 23, 1979|publisher=Family Hone Entertainment|oclc = 18329082}}</ref><ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Animalympics-VHS-Gilda-Radner/dp/B000009RXS Amazon.com: Animalympics VHS]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonanza.com/listings/Animalympics-VHS-Tape-Ages-5-12/386276651|title=Animalympics [VHS Tape] Ages 5-12|website=Bonanza}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, 2018, Hen's Tooth Video put out the first ever region 1 DVD release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Animalympics-Billy-Crystal/dp/B079FLRBR6|title=Animalympics|work=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]|date=April 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://shop.tcm.com/animalympics/759731416320 TCM Shop]</ref> In 2019, German label WinklerFilm put out a remastered DVD alongside the first ever Blu-Ray release worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Animalympics-Blu-ray/234142/|title=Animalympics Blu-ray|work=[[Blu-ray]]|date=May 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Laff-A-Lympics]]''\n* ''[[Sports Cartoons]]''\n* [[Olympic Games]]\n* ''[[Wide World of Sports (U.S. TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]''\n* ''[[Tron]]''\n* [[Furry fandom]]\n* [[1980 in television]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{AllMovie title|id=2475}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0078780}}\n* {{rotten tomatoes|animalympics}}\n* [http://www.the10ccfanclub.com/presskits/anim002.htm Press Kit]\n*[http://www.toonopedia.com/animalym.htm ''Animalympics''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/66fsZtMUL?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/animalym.htm Archived] from the original on April 4, 2012.\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/Animalympics_201704 Animalympics]'' on [[Internet Archive]]\n\n{{Steven Lisberger}}\n\n[[Category:1980 films]]\n[[Category:1980 animated films]]\n[[Category:1980s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. animated films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated sports films]]\n[[Category:Films about animals playing sports]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Steven Lisberger]]\n[[Category:Films about fictional Olympics-inspired events]]\n[[Category:Animated films about animals]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1980 animated film by Steven Lisberger}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Animalympics\n| image                    = Animalympics.jpg\n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  = Promotional release poster\n| genre                    = \n| creator                  = \n| based_on                 = \n| writer                   = [[Steven Lisberger]]<br>Michael Fremer\n| screenplay               = \n| story                    = Steven Lisberger<br>[[Roger Allers]]<br>John Norton\n| director                 = Steven Lisberger\n| starring                 = [[Billy Crystal]]<br>Michael Fremer<br>[[Gilda Radner]]<br>[[Harry Shearer]]\n| music                    = [[Graham Gouldman]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| producer                 = [[Donald Kushner]]<br>Steven Lisberger<br>Peggy Flook Lisberger (associate producer)\n| editor                   = Matt Cope\n| cinematography           = Ted Bemiller<br>Paul Nevitt<br>(animation camera)\n| runtime                  = 75 minutes\n| company                  = [[Lisberger Studios]]\n| distributor              = [[Warner Bros.]] (U.S. video and TV rights)\n| network                  = [[NBC]]\n| released                 = {{start date|1980|2|1}}\n| website                  = \n}}\n'''''Animalympics''''' is a 1980 [[Animated film|animated]] [[television film]] directed by [[Steven Lisberger]]<ref>[https://filmschoolrejects.com/27-things-we-learned-from-the-tron-commentary-89ed3c066303/ 27 Things We Learned from the 'Tron' Commentary - Film School Rejects]</ref> and produced by [[Lisberger Studios]] for the [[NBC]] network.<ref>[https://www.syfy.com/syfywire/how-furries-became-a-fandom How Furries Became a Fandom|SYFY]</ref> Originally commissioned as two separate specials, it spoofs the [[Summer Olympic Games|Summer]] and [[Winter Olympic Games]] and features the voices of [[Billy Crystal]], [[Gilda Radner]], [[Harry Shearer]] and Michael Fremer.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Woolery |first1=George W. |title=Animated TV Specials: The Complete Directory to the First Twenty-Five Years, 1962-1987 |date=1989 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |isbn=0-8108-2198-2 |accessdate=27 March 2020 |url=https://archive.org/details/animatedtvspecia0000wool/page/14/mode/2up |page=14}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film is a series of vignettes presented as the broadcast of the first animal Olympic Games through the fictional ZOO television network. The Games combine summer and winter Olympic events.\n\nThe event is covered mostly by Barbara Warblers, a stork, and \"anchorturtle\" Henry Hummel. The [[100-meter dash]] is covered in the style of a [[drag racing|drag race]] by Jackie Fuelit.\n\nUnlike the real Olympics, continents are represented rather than countries. The continents featured are North America, South America, [[Eurasia]], Europe, Africa, Australia, and Asia. Eurasia represents the [[USSR]], whereas Europe represents Western and Central Europe.\n\nThe only mention of areas other than continents are the New York City Rats soccer team, Dean Wilson being from California, a Central American marathon runner named Pep\u00e9 Repanosa, an [[Acapulco]] cliff diver named \"Primo Cabeza\", marathon runner Terry Hornsby being from [[Boulder, Colorado]], Ren\u00e9 Fromage being from France, and Kurt W\u00fcfner appearing at the [[Alpine skiing|downhill]] event right before a [[Scandinavia]]n is given a gold medal.\n\nAlthough many of the segments stand alone, there are some recurring events and important characters. The largest such story is the coverage of the [[marathon (sport)|marathon]], where competitors Ren\u00e9 Fromage and Kit Mambo are the favorites to win. Both are determined to win \u2013 Fromage having devoted his entire life to the marathon, Mambo determined to make a name for herself \u2013 they find themselves surprised when their minds wander to thoughts of mutual admiration and then to love, culminating in the pair holding hands for the rest of the race and crossing the finish line together.  Another important story is that of Kurt W\u00fcffner, a West German [[dachshund]] [[skiing|skier]], and his disappearance to [[Shangri-la|Dogra-la]] during a mountain climbing expedition shortly after the [[slalom skiing|slalom]] event.\n\nA minor story features an [[American alligator|alligator]] named Bolt Jenkins. He was \"born as a handbag\" and told he would never walk again. A song during his story reveals that he lives in the [[Sanitary sewer|sewers]]. After seeing a frog named Boris Amphibiensky break the world record for the [[high jump]], Jenkins has an epiphany, and becomes determined to break the record. Jenkins goes on to set world records in the high jump, the [[pole vault]], and later the [[100-meter dash]]. Jenkins sacrifices his gold medal in the hundred meter dash to an African competitor and favorite whom Jenkins considers to be his superior.\n\nSome events are only referenced rather than being covered. In the song \"We've Made It to the Top\", various events are shown that are otherwise not covered:\n*[[Hammer Throw]]\n*[[Shot put]]\n*[[Javelin throw|Javelin]]\n*[[Cycling]]\n*[[Relay Racing]]\n*[[Discus]]\n*[[Field hockey]]\n\nAlso referenced but not covered:\n*[[Boxing]]- only a highlight reel is provided after the match, despite being previewed as \"coming up after the basketball game\"\n*[[Speed Skating]]- previewed, but not actually shown\n*[[Water Polo]]- mentioned as happening earlier in the week\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Gilda Radner]] as Barbra Warblers / Brenda Springer / Cora Lee Perrier / Tatyana Tushenko / Dorrie Turnell / The Contessa\n* [[Billy Crystal]] as Rugs Turkell / Joey Gongolong / Art Antica\n* [[Harry Shearer]] as Keen Hacksaw / Mayor of Animalympic Island / Burnt Woody / Mark Spritz\n* Michael Fremer as Henry Hummel / Ren\u00e9 Fromage / Kit Mambo / Bolt Jenkins / Kurt Wuffner / Dean Wilson / Mele / Count Maurice Boar-Deaux / Jackie Fuelit / Bear McLane / Guy Lafluke / Bjorn Freeborg / Mamo Ululu\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/movies/Animalympics/|title=Animalympics|work=Behind the Voice Actors|date=September 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\n''Animalympics'' was commissioned by [[NBC]] in 1978, as the network intended [[Lisberger Studios]] to create it as two hour-long specials to be paired alongside coverage of both the [[1980 Winter Olympics]] and the [[1980 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] then held in [[Moscow]]. But after the [[Soviet Union]] had [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War|invaded and gained control of Afghanistan]], then [[United States]] President [[Jimmy Carter]] decided to [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|boycott the Moscow Summer Olympics]]. Because of this, NBC canceled its [[NBC Olympic broadcasts|Olympic coverage]] and the Animalympics Summer special.<ref name=\"Toon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toonopedia.com/animalym.htm|title=ANIMALYMPICS|work=[[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]|last=D. Markstein|first=Donald|accessdate=9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nHowever, from its conception, producer [[Donald Kushner]] and director Steven Lisberger intended the project as a feature-length theatrical release recorded and mixed in [[Dolby Stereo|Dolby surround sound]] via magnetically striped 35mm film even though The Winter Olympics special was considered for an [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film]] nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cartoonresearch.com/index.php/cartoons-considered-for-an-academy-award-1979/|title=Cartoons Considered For An Academy Award \u2013 1979 -|website=Cartoonresearch.com|accessdate=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAmong those who worked on ''Animalympics'' were art director/animator [[Roger Allers]], animation director [[Bill Kroyer]], and animator [[Brad Bird]]. Allers, who animated Kit Mambo, the lion star of ''Animalympics,'' went on to direct ''[[The Lion King]].''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reelzchannel.com/persondetail.aspx?personid=97623|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061030035246/http://www.reelzchannel.com/persondetail.aspx?personid=97623|url-status=dead|title=Roger Allers \u2013 Movies, Movie Clips and Trailers<!-- Bot generated title -->|archivedate=October 30, 2006}}</ref> Kroyer later wrote and directed the Oscar-nominated short ''[[Technological Threat]]'' and the animated feature ''[[FernGully: The Last Rainforest]].'' [[Brad Bird]] went on to work as story editor of ''[[The Simpsons]]'', and later achieved even greater success writing and directing ''[[The Iron Giant]]'', ''[[The Incredibles]]'' and ''[[Ratatouille (film)|Ratatouille]]''. Director Lisberger went on to conceive, co-write and direct the science fiction [[cult classic]] ''[[Tron]]'', which some of the ''Animalympics'' crew were involved in. Its soundtrack supervisor was Michael Fremer, who was involved in ''Animalympics'' as a co-writer, voice artist, dialogue/music track editor and sound mix supervisor. Fremer went on to supervise the Academy Award nominated soundtrack to ''[[Tron]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keyframeonline.com/Animation/Animalympics/434/|title=Animalympics|first=Athena|last=Cooper|website=Keyframeonline.com|accessdate=January 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919160109/http://www.keyframeonline.com/Animation/Animalympics/434/|archive-date=September 19, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Main|Animalympics (soundtrack)}}\n[[A&M Records]] in the US, and [[Mercury Records]] in Europe released an [[Animalympics soundtrack]] album, which has long been out of print. The music on this soundtrack was written and produced by [[Graham Gouldman]], who performed the tracks himself along with other members of [[10cc]] (Gouldman was the bassist for the band at the time).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Graham-Gouldman-Animalympics-Music-From-The-Original-Motion-Picture-Soundtrack/release/1050728 |title=Graham Gouldman \u2013 ''Animalympics \u2013 Music from the Original Motion Picture Soundtrack'' LP|website=Discogs.com|accessdate=1 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nPieces of classical music play in the film. \"The Hut on Hen's Legs (Baba Yaga)\" from ''[[Pictures at an Exhibition]]'' by [[Modest Mussorgsky]] plays during Tatyana Tushenko's floor exercises. \"March to the Scaffold\" from ''[[Symphonie fantastique]]'' by [[Hector Berlioz]] plays during the couple's figure skating. The 3rd movement from [[Symphony No. 4 (Brahms)|Symphony No. 4]] by [[Johannes Brahms]] plays during Dorie Turnell's skating performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.org/details/Animalympics_201704|title=Animalympics|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nDespite the 1980 NBC premiere being cancelled midway, [[Lisberger Studios]] prepared a theatrical version for overseas markets by editing together the [[Summer Olympic Games|Summer]] and [[Winter Olympic Games]] sections, alongside other additions and changes to increase it's run-time for theatrical exhibition. Though ''Animalympics'' never found a theatrical distributor in the U.S., [[Warner Bros.]] did acquire US home video and pay-TV distribution rights to it shortly after the NBC cancellation. It eventually got a full US TV premiere on NBC affiliate WPTZ on July 4, 1982. Animalympics also aired in its theatrical form on [[HBO]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lasertimepodcast.com/2016/08/15/animalympics-the-forgotten-animated-movie-about-animals-in-the-olympics/|title=Animalympics: The Forgotten Animated Movie About Animals in the Olympics|work=Laser Time Podcast|last=Ant|first=C.|date=August 15, 2016|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forcesofgeek.com/2016/08/run-forever-26-years-of-animalympics.html|title=Run Forever: 26 Years of 'Animalympics'|work=Forces of Geek|last=Maxwell|first=Erin|date=August 5, 2016|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/the-best-animated-kids-movies-youve-never-seen/|title=The Best Animated Kids Movies You've Probably Never Seen|work=[[/Film]]|last=Hunter|first=Rob|date=June 27, 2017|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> and [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] nationwide in summer 1984,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cartoonresearch.com/index.php/animation-anecdotes-277/|title=Animation Anecdotes #277: The Story of Animalympics.|work=Cartoon Research|date=August 26, 2016|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> as well as intermittently during the early to mid-1990s on [[The Disney Channel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newspaperarchive.com/corbin-times-tribune-feb-07-1998-p-18/|title=Corbin Times Tribune Archives, Feb 7, 1998, p. 18|date=February 7, 1998|website=NewspaperArchive.com}}</ref>\n\n===Availability===\nThe film was released on VHS by Warner Brothers, [[UAV Corporation]] and [[Family Home Entertainment]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Animalympics|date=December 23, 1979|publisher=Family Hone Entertainment|oclc = 18329082}}</ref><ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Animalympics-VHS-Gilda-Radner/dp/B000009RXS Amazon.com: Animalympics VHS]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonanza.com/listings/Animalympics-VHS-Tape-Ages-5-12/386276651|title=Animalympics [VHS Tape] Ages 5-12|website=Bonanza}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, 2018, Hen's Tooth Video put out the first ever region 1 DVD release.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Animalympics-Billy-Crystal/dp/B079FLRBR6|title=Animalympics|work=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]|date=April 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>[https://shop.tcm.com/animalympics/759731416320 TCM Shop]</ref> In 2019, German label WinklerFilm put out a remastered DVD alongside the first ever Blu-Ray release worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.blu-ray.com/movies/Animalympics-Blu-ray/234142/|title=Animalympics Blu-ray|work=[[Blu-ray]]|date=May 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Laff-A-Lympics]]''\n* ''[[Sports Cartoons]]''\n* [[Olympic Games]]\n* ''[[Wide World of Sports (U.S. TV series)|Wide World of Sports]]''\n* ''[[Tron]]''\n* [[Furry fandom]]\n* [[1980 in television]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{AllMovie title|id=2475}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0078780}}\n* {{rotten tomatoes|animalympics}}\n* [http://www.the10ccfanclub.com/presskits/anim002.htm Press Kit]\n*[http://www.toonopedia.com/animalym.htm ''Animalympics''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/66fsZtMUL?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/animalym.htm Archived] from the original on April 4, 2012.\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/Animalympics_201704 Animalympics]'' on [[Internet Archive]]\n\n{{Steven Lisberger}}\n\n[[Category:1980 films]]\n[[Category:1980 animated films]]\n[[Category:1980s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American independent films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. animated films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated sports films]]\n[[Category:Films about animals playing sports]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Steven Lisberger]]\n[[Category:Films about fictional Olympics-inspired events]]\n[[Category:Animated films about animals]]\n", "name_user": "TMProofreader", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eProduction)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Animalympics"}
{"title_page": "Jake Fromm", "text_new": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n<!-- DO NOT UNHIDE UNTIL HE IS OFFICIALLY DRAFTED\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Jake Fromm\n| image               = GA VS LSU E101318 73.jpg\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = Fromm in 2018\n| number              = \n| current_team        = \n| position            = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|1998|07|30}}\n| birth_place         = [[Warner Robins, Georgia]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 2\n| weight_lb           = 219\n| high_school         = [[Houston County High School (Georgia)|Houston County]] ([[Warner Robins, Georgia]])\n| college             = [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = \n| draftpick           = \n| pastteams           = \n* [[]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          = \n* ''USA Today'' High School All-American ([[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2016]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = 2020\n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = [[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n| statvalue1          = 0\u20130\n| statlabel2          = Passing yards\n| statvalue2          = 0\n| statlabel3          = Completion percentage\n| statvalue3          = 0\n| statlabel4          = [[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue4          = 0\n| nflnew              = \n| pfr                 =\n}}\n-->\n\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name=Jake Fromm\n|school=Georgia Bulldogs\n|image = GA VS LSU E101318 73.jpg\n|caption = Fromm in 2018\n|currentnumber=11\n|currentposition=[[Quarterback]]\n|class=Junior\n|major=Finance\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1998|07|30}}\n|birth_place=[[Warner Robins, Georgia]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=2\n|weight_lb=219\n|highlights=\n* [[Southeastern Conference football individual awards#Freshman of the Year|SEC Freshman of the Year]] (2017)\n* [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl Champion]] ([[2018 Rose Bowl|2018]])\n* [[SEC Championship Game|SEC Champion]] ([[2017 SEC Championship Game|2017]])\n* ''USA Today'' High School All-American ([[2016 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2016]])\n|highschool=[[Houston County High School (Georgia)|Houston County]]<br>([[Warner Robins, Georgia]])\n|bowlgames=\n*[[2018 Rose Bowl]]\n*[[2019 Sugar Bowl]]\n*[[2020 Sugar Bowl]]\n|pastschools=\n*[[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia]] (2017\u20132019)\n|espn=4240689\n}}\n'''William Jacob Fromm''' (born July 30, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]]. He played [[college football]] for the [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia Bulldogs]].\n\n==Early years==\nFromm was born in [[Warner Robins, Georgia]], on July 30, 1998. In his early years, Fromm played baseball with his local Warner Robins team, which came within two games of the [[2011 Little League World Series]] championship game. During the LLWS, Fromm at times would play in front of crowds larger than 30,000. He was one of the tournament's best players, hitting three home runs and driving in eight runs. He also struck out 11 batters as a pitcher.<ref>{{cite web |title=Video: Jake Fromm was a LLWS star before quarterbacking Georgia |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I0meQyLKy5A |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref> Fromm later attended [[Houston County High School (Georgia)|Houston County High School]] in Warner Robins. During his career he had 12,745 passing yards and 116 [[touchdowns]].<ref name=\"macon\">{{cite web|url=http://www.macon.com/sports/college/university-of-georgia/bulldogs-beat/uga-football/article132751369.html|title=Fromm shows competitive side in docuseries detailing his senior season|last=Butt|first=Jason|date=February 14, 2017|website=[[The Telegraph (Macon)|The Telegraph]]|publisher=[[McClatchy]]|accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref> Fromm was rated as a five-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]] and [[Scout.com]].<ref name=\"rivals\">{{cite web|url=https://n.rivals.com/content/prospects/2017/jake-fromm-2475|title=Jake Fromm, 2017 Pro-style quarterback|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rivals.com]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"scout\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scout.com/Player/Jake-Fromm-64794|title=Jake Fromm, Georgia, Pro-Style Quarterback|website=[[Scout.com]]|accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref> He originally committed to the [[University of Alabama]] to play college football but changed his commitment to the [[University of Georgia]].<ref name=\"al\">{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2016/03/why_4-star_qb_jake_fromm_flipp.html|title=Why 4-star QB Jake Fromm flipped commitment from Alabama to Georgia|last=Zenitz|first=Matt|date=March 21, 2016|website=AL.com|accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"espn\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/recruiting/football/story/_/id/14893543/qb-recruit-jake-fromm-commits-georgia-bulldogs|title=QB recruit Jake Fromm commits to Georgia Bulldogs|last=Crabtree|first=Jeremy|date=March 3, 2016|website=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref> Fromm's senior year was documented in the web-series ''QB1: Beyond the Lights'', created by [[Peter Berg]]. He was one of the three quarterbacks documented, the other two being [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]] commit [[Tate Martell]] and Tayvon Bowers who committed to [[Wake Forest Demon Deacons football|Wake Forest]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dawgnation.com/football/recruiting/watch-beyond-qb-lights-documentary-trailer-released-uga-freshman-jake-fromm|title=Watch: Documentary series trailer featuring UGA freshman Jake Fromm|last=Sentell|first=Jeff|date=February 2, 2017|website=DawgNation|language=en-US|access-date=September 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nFromm entered his true freshman year at Georgia in 2017 as the backup to [[Jacob Eason]]. In the first game of the season, after Eason suffered an injury, Fromm replaced him and completed 10 of 15 passes for 143 yards and a touchdown.<ref name=\"macon2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.macon.com/sports/college/university-of-georgia/bulldogs-beat/uga-football/article171212982.html|title=Far Fromm unprepared: UGA QB displays 'it-factor' to teammates|last=Butt|first=Jason|date=September 4, 2017|website=[[The Telegraph (Macon)|The Telegraph]]|publisher=[[McClatchy]]|accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"si\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2017/09/04/georgia-quarterback-jake-fromm|title=Georgia Quarterback Jake Fromm Is 'No Ordinary True Freshman'|last=Staples|first=Andy|date=September 4, 2017|website=[[Sports Illustrated]]|accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref> Fromm was then named the starter for the team's next game against [[2017 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]].<ref name=\"timesfreepress\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/sports/college/story/2017/sep/05/fromm-make-historic-start-georgia/447170/|title=Jake Fromm to make historic start for Georgia|last=Paschall|first=David|date=September 5, 2017|website=[[Chattanooga Times Free Press]]|publisher=[[WEHCO Media]]|accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"espn2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/20576953/georgia-bulldogs-qb-jacob-eason-notre-dame-fighting-irish-sprained-ligament-left-knee|title=UGA freshman Jake Fromm to start in place of injured Jacob Eason|last=Schlabach|first=Mark|date=September 4, 2017|website=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=September 6, 2017}}</ref> Fromm threw for 141 yards and a touchdown. In the next game, the Bulldogs defeated [[2017 Samford Bulldogs football team|Samford]] with a 42\u201314 win. After a win against Vanderbilt, Fromm played his best game against Missouri. He threw for 326 yards and completed 18 of 26 passes. This performance led the Bulldogs to be the third-ranked team in the nation. After a 42\u20137 win vs Florida, the Bulldogs became No. 1 after Penn State lost. Fromm and the Bulldogs would eventually go on to win the 2017 SEC Championship against Auburn. He was named co-newcomer of the year by the Associated Press.<ref>[https://collegefootball.ap.org/atnonline/article/georgia-auburn-split-top-awards-ap-all-sec-football-team Georgia, Auburn split top awards on AP All-SEC football team]</ref>{{Failed verification|date=September 2019}}\n\nHe led Georgia to a 54\u201348 victory over Oklahoma in double overtime in the Rose Bowl on January 1, 2018, to earn them a spot in the CFP final against Alabama. Fromm and the Bulldogs went on to lose to Alabama in the College Football National Championship, 23\u201326. Fromm threw for 232 yards, a touchdown and two interceptions, while completing 16 of 32 passes.\n\nOn January 8, 2020, Fromm announced his intention to skip his senior season at Georgia, having declared for the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/28447520/georgia-quarterback-jake-fromm-entering-nfl-draft|title=Georgia quarterback Fromm entering NFL draft|last=Schlabach|first=Mark|date=2020-01-08|website=ESPN.com|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>\n\n===College statistics===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|! colspan=\"18\" style=\"{{CollegePrimaryStyle|Georgia Bulldogs|color=white}};\" |<center>'''Georgia Bulldogs'''</center>\n|- align=\"center\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Class\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Position\n! rowspan=\"2\"| GP\n! colspan=\"9\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"4\"| Rushing\n|-\n! Comp !! Att !! Pct !! Yards !! Y/A !! AY/A !! TD !! INT !! QBR !! Att !! Yards !! Avg !! TD\n|-\n! [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017]] !! [[Freshman]] !! [[Quarterback|QB]]\n| 15 || 181 || 291 || 62.2 || 2615